english:
  title: Record of Geumgol Mountain
  author: Lee Ju
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Geumgol Mountain stands twenty li west of Jindo County seat. Its central peak rises precipitous and grand, all four sides wreathed in stone, and from afar resembles a jade lotus blossom. To the northwest it touches the sea. The earth's vein winds and coils, flowing southward for two li before becoming Gan Peak, then eastward again for two li to become Yongjang Mountain, where it finally ceases at Bigyepa Ferry. The mountain's perimeter spans some thirty li or more. Below lies the ancient foundation of a great temple called Haewon Temple, where stands a nine-tiered stone pagoda. West of the pagoda lies an abandoned well, and above it three caves—the lowest called the Western Cave, situated at the western foot of the mountain. When it was first built remains unknown. Recently, a monk named Ilhaeng carved sixteen arhats from fragrant wood and installed them in this cave. Beside the cave stand six or seven halls of ancient foundation where monks now dwell. The uppermost is the Upper Cave, situated at the eastern summit of the central peak. The slanting cliff and sheer precipice drop so far that even the nimble monkey cannot cross. From the east there is nowhere to grasp or set foot. Coming from the Western Cave and ascending eastward, the path proves treacherous beyond measure—clinging to the cliff, rolling over stones, advancing inch by inch. After about one li, a stone peak rises alone, too high to leap across. Rocks are piled into thirteen stepping tiers. Looking down reveals no bottom; both heart and eyes grow dizzy. Ascending this reaches the summit. From the summit, descending eastward some thirty paces, the bare stone is carved into twelve concave footholds for climbing up and down. Below these, ten more paces, lies the Upper Cave. Beyond this, several paces northward along the rocky face, another bare cliff has been carved, suspended in empty space, dropping eight or nine paces eastward to form the Eastern Cave. The front halls and kitchens have all crumbled in wind and rain. On the cliff north of the cave, a stone Maitreya Buddha was carved by an ancient county magistrate named Liu Haochi. The monks say that in ancient times this mountain often displayed miraculous signs, sending forth light each year to show divine marvels. When people prayed for aid against plague, drought, or flood, their prayers were ever answered. But since the Maitreya was carved, the mountain ceased to shine. Perhaps Liu was not merely some heterodox charlatan like one Kim Dong, but rather a person who suppressed the mountain's spirit. Though such talk seems wild, it merits consideration.

    In autumn of the Muo year, I came to this island in exile for my crimes. That winter I wandered this mountain, marking in my memory the three caves of which I had heard. Four years passed. In autumn of the Imseol year, the ninth month, the Crown Prince received his investiture, and on that very day a general amnesty was proclaimed throughout the realm. Yet I alone, among those officials and scholars punished in the Muo year, was excluded from this clemency. I privately lamented: When a gentleman of virtue lives in this world, he must hold fast to loyalty and filial piety. Now my crimes run deep; I have become refuse cast aside by the throne. I wish to serve as a loyal minister, yet cannot be loyal to my king. I wish to be a dutiful son, yet cannot honor my parents. I have brothers, friends, and family, yet cannot enjoy the company of brothers, friends, and family. I am not human. My will to live ebbed ever further.

    One day, bearing wine in a small flask, I walked alone to the Western Cave. I brought with me monks Yeongyong and Jisun, and we made directly for the Upper Cave. The cave, with its attached Buddha hall and refectory, contained but two rooms. Long abandoned, no monks dwelt there. Fallen leaves blocked the entrance; dust and sand filled the chambers. Mountain wind lashed it; sea mist seeped in. Rank miasma accumulated unbearably. I swept away the dust and sand, plastered the walls, cut wood for the stove, opened the doors to let in air. At midday I ate one bowl of rice; at dawn and dusk, one cup of tea. I listened to the roosters crow to know the morning, watched the tide to know the hour. I slept as I wished, moved as I pleased. I composed five verses, which Jisun would recite each night while I lay listening at the fifth watch—a singular refinement indeed. Thus I passed half a month.

    Then the county magistrate Lee Sejin came bearing wine to comfort me, saying: "This place is perilous; you should descend quickly. If you wish to dwell with monks, the Western Cave would be more suitable." Officials Choi Takkgyeong and Park Igyeong sent letters urging: "We hear you lodge in the Upper Cave, treading upon unforeseen danger—this is not the conduct of one who understands destiny." Sun Yeolim came from the capital bearing the king's commission to inquire into the people's welfare, and through my friends conveyed harsh reproach. I replied: "Friends reprove with sincerity, not deception. I was foolish and did not know the path of ambition steeper than nine-fold mountains. I did not cease but pressed forward, and thereby wrecked myself. Now dwelling in this cave, I know not its dangers. Should I stumble once and injure my parents' sacred body, no greater unfilial act could exist."

    I took leave of my two teachers, Jisun and Yeongyong, and descended. They walked me down to the stone pagoda of Haewon Temple, where they said: "A mountain monk's tracks are like clouds without direction—how could he have fixed dwelling? Soon I too shall receive grace and depart. How could I remain long at Geumgol? Would you not set down words to preserve our memory?" I answered: "Your words merit recording. I consulted the Geographical Records of Worthy Places, and found Geumgol Mountain not listed among the famous peaks of this island, nor the three caves recorded among the temples. This is an omission in the official records—a great misfortune for Geumgol. Now by your words, I shall record Geumgol Mountain, so that those who read this in times to come will know that on this island stands Geumgol, that within this mountain are three caves, and that your reverences dwelt here with an old man. Will this not preserve what was done today as history?" My teachers agreed. I gathered verses composed during my days and thus made this Record of Geumgol Mountain to leave in the cave. I spent twenty-three days upon the mountain.

    In the tenth month of winter, the Imseol year of the Hongzhi era, Lee Ju of Cheolseong records this.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Geumgol means 'golden bones'—the mountain's name itself suggests both beauty and endurance.
  - key: ''
    value: The Muo year refers to 1498 in the lunar calendar.
  - key: ''
    value: The Imseol year is four years later, 1502.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'nine-fold mountains' alludes to the treacherous path of political ambition in the capital.
  - key: ''
    value: Lee Ju's voluntary retreat to the Upper Cave mirrors a classical theme of the virtuous man withdrawing from an unjust world, even while cherishing duty unfulfilled.
